## Bug Analysis

The `if/else` logic is **inverted**. The current code:
- Marks unseen items as `true` in `seen` → wrong, should add to `duplicates`
- Pushes to `duplicates` when item is already seen → wrong, should mark as seen

### Fixed Code

```javascript
function findDuplicates(arr) {
  const seen = {};
  const duplicates = [];
  for (let i = 0; i < arr.length; i++) {
    if (seen[arr[i]]) {
      duplicates.push(arr[i]);
    } else {
      seen[arr[i]] = true;
    }
  }
  return duplicates;
}
```

### Example
```javascript
findDuplicates([1, 2, 3, 2, 4, 3, 5]);
// Returns: [2, 3]
```

---

**Bonus issue to consider:** if a value appears 3+ times, it will be added to `duplicates` multiple times. If you want each duplicate reported only once, add a check:

```javascript
if (seen[arr[i]] && !duplicates.includes(arr[i])) {
  duplicates.push(arr[i]);
} else {
  seen[arr[i]] = true;
}
```

Or more efficiently, use a `Set` for the duplicates collection:

```javascript
function findDuplicates(arr) {
  const seen = new Set();
  const duplicates = new Set();
  for (const val of arr) {
    if (seen.has(val)) duplicates.add(val);
    else seen.add(val);
  }
  return [...duplicates];
}
```

